@harupy awesome, I'm a fan of this as a workaround given that Plotly doesn't allow making the tooltips "sticky". I guess if users have a plot with many runs (many overlapping lines), they can isolate the run (line) of interest by double-clicking it in the legend on the right, then click the selected line. It does seem a little hard to discover though.

@gioa @mateiz @clemens-db any thoughts here?

Also, I was wondering if we could also/instead add a link to the run in the plotly legend, e.g:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2358483/72107654-9a406600-32e6-11ea-9266-4b380972c03f.png)

However this seems difficult to do - it's possible to change the legend text [here](https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/blob/3440c127c9e27d8b5cf6affd0b1ced3890720e8f/mlflow/server/js/src/components/MetricsPlotView.js#L29) to include a hyperlink, e.g. by replacing that line with something like

```
    if (isComparing) {
      legendText += `, ${Utils.truncateString(runDisplayName, MAX_RUN_NAME_DISPLAY_LENGTH)}`;
      return `${legendText} <a href='http://google.com'>(link)</a>`;
    }
```

However, customizing the toggle behavior of the legend (getting the link text to actually trigger when clicked, instead of toggling the legend) seems tricky.

@smurching 

> Also, do you know if this modal behavior is also possible to implement e.g. for the scatter plot & parallel coordinates plot?

Haven't tried yet, but I think it's possible to implement this for scatter and parallel coordinate plots.

@gioa @clemens-db Thanks for the feedback. The popover looks nice, but not sure if it's possible to add a popover on the plotly chart. Let me try.

> One consideration is what happens when there are multiple overlapping data points. The current plot shows all of those datapoints at the same time when you hover.

Plotly has an option named `closest` for `hovermode`. With this option enabled, the hover event occurs on the closest point ([ref](https://plot.ly/python/reference/#layout-hovermode)).
